   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C0079_1833_08_06_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworth's Town
                  <date when="1833-08-06">Aug 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1833</date>
               </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>It is one of the privileges<lb/>
               of the republic of letters<lb/>
               that the individuals may<lb/>
               be supposed to be known<lb/>
               to each other - and I <hi rend="underline">will</hi>
               <lb/>
               flatter myself (being an<lb/>
               Irish woman) that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RushR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Rush</persName>
               <lb/>
               may be acquainted with<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xmlEdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName> - I have<lb/>
               received so much kindness<lb/>
               and so many testimonies<lb/>
               of regard from his <choice>
                  <orig>country<lb/>
               -men</orig>
                  <reg>countrymen</reg>
               </choice> and country women<lb/>
               that I feel I am better known<lb/>
               there than in my own <choice>
                  <orig>coun<lb/>
               try </orig>
                  <reg>country</reg>
               </choice>(meaning <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>).<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Let me hope therefore that<lb/>
               you will not think <add>me</add>
               <choice>
                  <orig>presump<lb/>
               tuous</orig>
                  <reg>presumptuous</reg>
               </choice> in intruding thus<lb/>
               upon you with my <hi rend="underline">homage</hi>
               <lb/>
                  - this not French <hi rend="underline">hommage</hi>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C0079_1833_08_06_page02.jpg"/>
               but perfectly sincere plain<lb/>
               English esteem and <choice>
                  <orig>admi<lb/>
               ration </orig>
                  <reg>admiration</reg>
               </choice>-- <hi rend="underline">We</hi> meaning<lb/>
               a large literary family<lb/>
               have been this last week<lb/>
                  reading <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RushR1">Rush</persName>'s account<lb/>
               of the Court of London -- with<lb/>
               which we have been delighted<lb/>
               for many reasons -<lb/>
               In the first place, it is<lb/>
               exceedingly entertaining and<lb/>
               interesting merely considered<lb/>
               as a book for <del>be read by the</del>
               <lb/>
               general readers --<lb/>
               In the next place it is the<lb/>
               best and most honest <choice>
                  <orig>diplo-<lb/>
               matic </orig>
                  <reg>diplomatic</reg>
               </choice>book I ever read --<lb/>
               The must intelligible, and<lb/>
               the most honorable to the<lb/>
               diplomatic corps - showing<lb/>
               that plain dealing is the<lb/>
               shortest line between <add>any</add> two points,<lb/>
               and that honesty even in<lb/>
               diplomacy <hi rend="underline">is</hi> the best policy<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C0079_1833_08_06_page03.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RipoG1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Robinson</persName> (the present<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RipoG1">Lord Rippon</persName>) made an<lb/>
               opening of the budget as<lb/>
               a financier some years<lb/>
               ago so clear in laying down<lb/>
               the principles of taxation &amp;<lb/>
               the intricacy of national <choice>
                  <orig>ac<lb/>
               counts </orig>
                  <reg>accounts</reg>
               </choice>that I considered it<lb/>
               at the time &amp; find it has since<lb/>
               been considered as marking<lb/>
               a new era in <hi rend="underline">fiscal speaking</hi>
               <lb/>
               I consider your books in<lb/>
               the same light as to diplomacy<lb/>
               But in a still higher<lb/>
               point of view I value this<lb/>
               work as certain to produce<lb/>
               salutory effect between<lb/>
               these countries and <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName>
               <lb/>
               -- It is written in such a<lb/>
               mild liberal candid <hi rend="underline">just</hi>
               <lb/>
               spirit so full of <del>natural</del>
               <lb/>
               true love for country &amp;<lb/>
               so free from that national<lb/>
               egoism &amp; <del>
                  <unclear/>
               </del>
               <choice>
                  <orig>osten<lb/>
               tatious</orig>
                  <reg>ostentatious</reg>
               </choice> feeling for <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName>
               <lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">exclusively</hi>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C0079_1833_08_06_page04.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">before the Old World</hi> that it<lb/>
               is in itself the best possible<lb/>
               answer to the attacks that<lb/>
               have been made on this<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">count</hi> upon Americans<lb/>
               It is the best <hi rend="underline">evidence</hi> that<lb/>
               in the higher ranks of mind in<lb/>
               all countries men are<lb/>
               the same in genuine<lb/>
               politeness of manner &amp;<lb/>
               well bred spirit <choice>
                  <orig>indepen<lb/>
               dent</orig>
                  <reg>independent</reg>
               </choice> of all form -<lb/>
               It would highly gratify<lb/>
               me to hear from you that<lb/>
               you do not think I set an<lb/>
               impertinent value upon<lb/>
               the expression of my own<lb/>
               opinions &amp; feelings in<lb/>
               thus wafting this incense<lb/>
               to you from myself &amp; my<lb/>
               own family<lb/>
               We closed your volume sorry<lb/>
               that we had not another to<lb/>
               open -- I am Sir with just respect<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>Your obliged reader<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C0079_1833_08_06_page05.jpg"/>
            <closer>
